<Layout title="Functional Status & Mobility Assessment Tools" description="Functional status and mobility assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Functional Status &amp; Mobility</div>
  <h1>Functional Status &amp; Mobility Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Tools for measuring activities of daily living, functional independence, mobility, and physical performance.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Barthel Index</strong> — 10-item ADL assessment: feeding, bathing, grooming, dressing, bowel/bladder control, toilet use, transfers, mobility, stairs. Score 0–100; lower scores indicate greater dependence.</li>
      <li><strong>Katz Index of Independence in ADL</strong> — Six-activity independence assessment for older adults: bathing, dressing, toileting, transferring, continence, and feeding. Grade A (fully independent) to G (dependent in all).</li>
      <li><strong>FIM (Functional Independence Measure)</strong> — 18-item assessment across motor and cognitive domains. Each item scored 1–7 (total dependence to complete independence); total 18–126.</li>
      <li><strong>WeeFIM</strong> — Pediatric adaptation of FIM for children 6 months–7 years. Assesses self-care, sphincter control, transfers, locomotion, communication, and social cognition.</li>
      <li><strong>IADL Scale (Instrumental Activities of Daily Living)</strong> — Eight higher-level function domains: telephone use, shopping, food preparation, housekeeping, laundry, transportation, medications, finances. Used for community-dwelling older adults.</li>
      <li><strong>COPM (Canadian Occupational Performance Measure)</strong> — Client-centered occupational therapy outcome measure; patient identifies and rates performance and satisfaction in self-care, productivity, and leisure.</li>
      <li><strong>6-Minute Walk Test (6MWT)</strong> — Distance walked in 6 minutes on flat surface; functional capacity benchmark in cardiopulmonary rehabilitation, heart failure, and pulmonary hypertension.</li>
      <li><strong>2-Minute Walk Test</strong> — Abbreviated walk test for patients who cannot complete 6MWT; validated in elderly populations and for monitoring in clinical settings.</li>
      <li><strong>10-Meter Walk Test</strong> — Gait speed measurement over 10 meters; comfortable and fast speeds both assessed. Normal comfortable gait speed &gt;1.0 m/s; &lt;0.8 m/s indicates risk.</li>
      <li><strong>SPPB (Short Physical Performance Battery)</strong> — Three-component lower extremity performance battery: standing balance, 4-meter walk, and chair stands. Score 0–12; &lt;8 indicates high disability risk.</li>
      <li><strong>Grip Strength Testing</strong> — Hand dynamometry measuring maximal grip force; sarcopenia screening criterion (men &lt;27 kg, women &lt;16 kg by EWGSOP2). Correlates with overall muscle strength and functional outcomes.</li>
      <li><strong>Lovett Scale (Manual Muscle Testing)</strong> — Muscle strength graded 0–5: 0 (no contraction) to 5 (normal strength against full resistance). Foundation of neurological and musculoskeletal assessment.</li>
      <li><strong>Modified Ashworth Scale</strong> — Spasticity grading 0–4 (with 1+): 0 = no increase in tone; 4 = affected part rigid. Widely used in stroke, MS, and spinal cord injury rehabilitation.</li>
      <li><strong>Tardieu Scale</strong> — Dynamic spasticity assessment; measures velocity-dependent resistance at two speeds. More specific than Ashworth for neural (spasticity) vs. non-neural (contracture) components.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
